Q1: ANN with Vector Embeddings (GloVe + SentenceTransformers)
[Overview]
For Q1, I implemented a multi-task feedforward ANN (MLP) to predict Emotion (regression), Empathy (regression), and EmotionalPolarity (classification) from each conversational turn. I experimented with two fixed-length embedding approaches: SentenceTransformer sentence embeddings and GloVe word embeddings (mean pooled).
P1(1)

[Implementation Details]
1) Input / Output
    - Input text: text column (each row is a conversational turn)
    - Targets (train/dev only):
        Emotion (float, regression)
        Empathy (float, regression)
        EmotionalPolarity (int, classification)
2) Preprocessing / Data Cleaning
    - CSV reading used:
        pd.read_csv(..., engine="python", on_bad_lines="skip")
        - because the dev file contained malformed lines/quotes that caused parser errors.
        - The dev dataset had an extra column compared to train, so I aligned dev to train columns by using the intersection of columns.
        - Polarity label cleanup: The train set had a very rare label 3 (only 1 sample). To avoid unstable training, I merged label 3 into label 2, resulting in 3 classes {0, 1, 2} for EmotionalPolarity.
3) Embedding Methods
    A. SentenceTransformer embeddings
        - Model: sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2
        - Each text was encoded into a single vector using the SentenceTransformer encoder.
        - Used normalized embeddings (normalize_embeddings=True) for stability.
    B. GloVe embeddings
        - Model: glove-wiki-gigaword-300 via gensim.downloader
        - Tokenized text using a simple regex and computed a sentence vector by:
            - collecting all in-vocabulary word vectors
            - taking the mean of those vectors
            - if no known words exist, used a zero vector
4) ANN Model Architecture (PyTorch)
    - A shared MLP backbone + three task-specific heads:
        - Backbone: Linear → ReLU → Dropout → Linear → ReLU → Dropout
        - Head 1: Emotion regression (1 output)
        - Head 2: Empathy regression (1 output)
        - Head 3: Polarity classification (3 logits)
Hyperparameters:
    - hidden size = 256
    - dropout = 0.2
    - batch size = 64
    - optimizer = Adam
    - learning rate = 1e-3
    - training device: CPU

5) Loss Functions (Multi-task)
    Total loss = Emotion loss + Empathy loss + Polarity loss
        - Emotion: MSELoss
        - Empathy: MSELoss
        - EmotionalPolarity: CrossEntropyLoss

[Development Results]
ANN + SentenceTransformer (all-MiniLM-L6-v2)
    - Dev Emotion MAE: 0.5074
    - Dev Empathy MAE: 0.7214
    - Dev Polarity Accuracy: 0.6891
    - Dev Polarity weighted F1: 0.6774

Output prediction file:
    - outputs/predictions_ann_sbert.csv

ANN + GloVe (glove-wiki-gigaword-300)
(Best epoch: Epoch 7)
    - Dev Emotion MAE: 0.5171
    - Dev Empathy MAE: 0.7427
    - Dev Polarity Accuracy: 0.6705
    - Dev Polarity weighted F1: 0.6556

Output prediction file: outputs/predictions_ann_glove.csv

Conclusion: SentenceTransformer embeddings performed better than GloVe on the dev set across all three tasks.

[Notes on Model Choices]
- I started with sentence-level embeddings (SentenceTransformer) because they provide strong semantic representations with minimal feature engineering.
- I used GloVe as a classical baseline by mean-pooling word vectors; this is simpler but loses some context compared to SentenceTransformer.
- I merged the extremely rare polarity label 3 into 2 to prevent instability in classification training.

[How to Run (Q1)]
Folder setup
    -Place the dataset files in:
        data/trac2_CONVT_train.csv
        data/trac2_CONVT_dev.csv
        data/trac2_CONVT_test.csv

Install dependencies
    Run in terminal:
        pip install pandas numpy scikit-learn torch sentence-transformers gensim scipy tqdm
    Run SentenceTransformer ANN
        python ann_sbert.py
    This will produce:
        outputs/predictions_ann_sbert.csv
Run GloVe ANN
    python ann_glove.py
This will produce:
    outputs/predictions_ann_glove.csv